{{Wikispecies|Carduelis corsicana|''Carduelis corsicana''}}
The '''Corsican finch''' ('''''Carduelis corsicana'''''), also known as the '''Corsican citril finch''' or '''Mediterranean citril finch''', is a species of [[passerine]] bird belonging to the [[Family (taxonomy)|family]] [[Fringillidae]], the "true" finches. This species is endemic to [[Corsica]] and [[Sardinia]] and nearby islands in France and Italy.

==Taxonomy==
The Corsican finch was first formally [[Species description|formal description]] as ''Citrinella corsicana'' in 1899 by the German zoologist [[Alexander Koenig]] with its [[Type locality (biology)|type locality]] given as Corsica.<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Koenig | first=Alexander | author-link=Alexander Koenig | year=1899 | title=Eine neu Vogelart von der Insel Corsica | language=de | journal=Ornithologische Monatsberichte | volume=7 | issue=7 | page=120 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/32584537 }}</ref> It was formerly regarded a [[subspecies]] of the [[citril finch]] (''C. citrinella''), but it differs in [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]] and vocalizations as well as [[mtDNA]] [[DNA sequence|sequence]] and they are now considered distinct species.<ref name = Forschler2007>{{cite journal | last1 = Förschler | first1 = M.I. | last2 = Kalko | first2 = E.K.V. | year = 2007 | title = Geographical differentiation, acoustic adaptation and species boundaries in mainland citril finches and insular Corsican finches, superspecies ''Carduelis'' [''citrinella''] | journal=Journal of Biogeography | volume = 34 | issue = 9| pages = 1591–1600 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2699.2007.01722.x | bibcode = 2007JBiog..34.1591F | s2cid = 28037228 | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/227511008 }}</ref><ref name = Forschler2009>{{cite journal |author1=Förschler, Marc |author2=Senar, Juan Carlos |author3=Perret, Philippe |author4=Björklund, Mats |year=2009 |title=The species status of the Corsican finch ''Carduelis corsicana'' assesed by three genetic markers with different rates of evolution |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |volume=52 |issue=1 |pages=234–40 |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2009.02.014|pmid=19249374 |bibcode=2009MolPE..52..234F }}</ref> The Corsican finch is classified within the genus ''Carduelis'', with the citril finch being its closest relative, although the Corsican finch split from the citril finch lineage around 1.37 million years ago. However, they are more closely related to one another than either is to the [[European goldfinch]] (''C. carduelis'').<ref name = Forschler2009/> The genus ''[[Carduelis]]'' is classified within the [[subfamily]] [[Carduelinae]] of the family Fringillidae.<ref name=Zuccon2012>{{cite journal | last1=Zuccon | first1=Dario | last2=Prŷs-Jones | first2=Robert | last3=Rasmussen | first3=Pamela C. | last4=Ericson | first4=Per G.P. | date=February 2012 | title=The phylogenetic relationships and generic limits of finches (Fringillidae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=62 | issue=2 | pages=581–596 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2011.10.002 | url=http://www.nrm.se/download/18.9ff3752132fdaeccb6800010935/Zuccon%20et%20al%202012.pdf | pmid=22023825 | bibcode=2012MolPE..62..581Z | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610193317/http://www.nrm.se/download/18.9ff3752132fdaeccb6800010935/Zuccon%20et%20al%202012.pdf | archive-date=2015-06-10 }}</ref>

{{Phylogeny/Carduelis}}

==Description==
The Corsican finch is a small finch, with a length of between {{cvt|11.5|and|12.5|cm}}. It is very similar to the citril finch but it has a brown back marked with dark streaks and the yellow underparts and face have less of a green tinge than seen in the citril finch. It also has greyish rather than olive uppertail coverts.<ref name = Collins>{{cite book |author=Lars Svensson |author2=Killian Mullarney |author3=Dan Zetterström |name-list-style=& |year=2022 |title=Collins Bird Guide |edition=3 |pages=394–395|isbn=978-0-00-854745-5 |publisher=William Collins}}</ref> The colours of the females are duller than the males.<ref name = eBird>{{cite web |url=https://ebird.org/species/corfin1 |title=Corsican Finch |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=eBird}}</ref>

===Vocalisations===
The Corsican finch has vocalisations similar to those of the citril finch but the flight call has been described as weaker and moretremulous while the song is longer, with more structure and has been compared to that of a [[Eurasian wren]] (''Troglodytes troglodytes'').<ref name = Collins/>

==Distribution and habitat==
The Corsican finch is found on Corsica and Sardinia as well as the islands of [[Gorgona (Italy)|Gorgona]], [[Capraia]] and [[Elba]] in the [[Tuscan Archipelago]].<ref name = ouiseaux>{{cite web |url=https://www.oiseaux.net/birds/corsican.finch.html |title=Corsican Finch ''Carduelis corsicana'' - Venturon corse |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=oiseaux.net}}</ref> During the breeding season the Corsican finch is found from lowland [[garrigue]] up to montane areas where it inhabits dry scrub and conifer forests, mainly of European black pine (''[[Pinus nigra]]'') and maritime pine (''[[Pinus pinaster|P. pinaster]]''), which may be open or semi open. It can also be found in [[heathland]] with [[Tree heath]] (''[[Erica (plant)|Erica]]'') and bushes, mostly ''[[Genista]]'' and bramble (''[[Rubus]]''), as well as [[alder]] (''Alnus'') groves and areas where there are lightly scattered conifers. In subalpine zones this species occurs in low [[juniper]] (''Juniperus''). When not breeding these birds make local movements into areas of scrub in lowland valleys, plains and coastal areas.<ref name = Birdlife>{{cite web |url=https://datazone.birdlife.org/species/factsheet/corsican-finch-carduelis-corsicana |title=Corsican Finch |access-date=8 April 2025 |publisher=Birdlife International}}</ref>

==Biology==
The Corsican finch is an altitudinal migrant, with montaine breeding birds spending the non breeding season at lower elevations. The breeding season occurs from mid-march to, at least, June. They build a nest which is a loosely woven, shallow cup of fine grasses, plant fibres and down, moss, animal hair and feathers. The nest is typically located up to {{cvt|3|m}} above the ground in low shrubs or trees. The clutch is between two and five eggs. The diet of the Corsican finchIincluds the seeds of European black pine, grasses (''[[Poa]]'', ''[[Briza]]'') and herbs.  In Sardinia this species feeds on the larval and pupal stages of [[ermine moth]]s.<ref name = Birdlife/>

